    {
      "id": 17,
      "title": "Extend MCP Server Tools for Hybrid QDrant-Neo4j Search",
      "description": "Modify the MCP server tools to support hybrid search queries that combine vector search results from QDrant with graph-based relationship queries from Neo4j, enhancing search capabilities in the existing search module without breaking current interfaces.",
      "details": "Update the search logic in packages/qdrant-loader-mcp-server/src/qdrant_loader_mcp_server/search/ to orchestrate hybrid queries: first, perform a vector similarity search using QDrant's Query API to retrieve top-k candidates based on semantic relevance. Next, use Neo4j Cypher queries to fetch and score relationship-based context for these candidates (e.g., entity connections, graph distance, centrality). Implement a result fusion mechanism that combines QDrant's vector scores with Neo4j-derived relationship scores, allowing for configurable weighting (e.g., via query parameters or config). Ensure the hybrid search is exposed through the existing MCP tool interfaces, maintaining backward compatibility. Add robust error handling for both QDrant and Neo4j failures, and document the new query parameters and result schema. Reference best practices from GraphRAG and Qdrant hybrid search documentation for implementation patterns and scoring strategies.[1][2][3][4]",
      "testStrategy": "1. Write unit and integration tests to verify that hybrid search queries return results that reflect both vector similarity and graph relationship relevance. 2. Test with mock and real data to ensure that the result fusion logic correctly combines QDrant and Neo4j scores according to configurable weights. 3. Validate that existing MCP tool interfaces and legacy search queries remain functional and unchanged. 4. Simulate QDrant and Neo4j outages to confirm robust error handling and fallback behavior. 5. Review documentation and ensure new query parameters and result formats are clearly described.",
      "status": "pending",
      "dependencies": [
        7,
        8
      ],
      "priority": "high",
      "subtasks": []
    },
    {
      "id": 18,
      "title": "Implement Backward Compatibility Layer and Migration Utilities for QDrant Loader Users",
      "description": "Create a backward compatibility layer to ensure all existing QDrant Loader functionality continues to work unchanged, with Graphiti features opt-in via configuration, and provide migration utilities for gradual adoption of graph features.",
      "details": "Develop a compatibility module that intercepts and adapts calls to the QDrant Loader core, ensuring legacy APIs, configuration formats, and workflows remain fully functional. Introduce a configuration flag (e.g., `enable_graphiti`) that defaults to false, so Graphiti-based entity extraction and graph storage are only activated when explicitly enabled. Refactor initialization and processing logic to branch cleanly between legacy and hybrid modes, ensuring no changes to existing data models, endpoints, or user-facing behaviors unless the new features are opted in. Build migration utilities (CLI tools or scripts) to help users convert existing data and configurations to support graph features, including step-by-step guides and dry-run options. Maintain comprehensive documentation on compatibility guarantees and migration paths. Collaborate closely with the teams responsible for Tasks 16 and 17 to ensure seamless integration and no regressions in document processing or search workflows.",
      "testStrategy": "Develop a comprehensive regression test suite that runs all existing QDrant Loader workflows (document ingestion, search, update, and deletion) with Graphiti features disabled, verifying identical behavior and outputs as before. Add integration tests that enable Graphiti features via configuration and validate hybrid operation. Test migration utilities on real and synthetic legacy datasets, ensuring data integrity and smooth transitions. Include negative tests to confirm that enabling Graphiti does not affect legacy users. Perform manual and automated user acceptance testing with representative legacy configurations.",
      "status": "pending",
      "dependencies": [
        16,
        17
      ],
      "priority": "high",
      "subtasks": []
    },
    {
      "id": 19,
      "title": "Enhance Data Source Connectors to Extract and Store Metadata for Graph Relationships",
      "description": "Extend the Git, Confluence, and JIRA connectors to extract and persist metadata such as author information, timestamps, cross-references, project relationships, and contextual data to enrich the knowledge graph, without altering the core connector interfaces.",
      "details": "Update each data source connector (Git, Confluence, JIRA) to extract relevant metadata during data ingestion. For Git, capture commit author, commit timestamp, file references, and branch/merge relationships. For Confluence, extract page authors, creation/modification timestamps, parent/child page links, and embedded cross-references. For JIRA, use the REST API to retrieve issue metadata including reporter, assignee, creation/update timestamps, project and epic links, and references to related issues (e.g., via 'relates to', 'blocks', or 'duplicates' fields)[1][5]. Design a metadata extraction layer within each connector that collects this information and serializes it into a structured format (e.g., JSON or dict) alongside the main content payload. Ensure this metadata is stored in a way that is accessible to downstream graph processing (e.g., as part of the document object or a dedicated metadata field). Do not modify the public connector interfaces; instead, use internal extension points or hooks. Update documentation to specify what metadata is extracted per source and how it is structured. Ensure compatibility with the configuration management system for enabling/disabling metadata extraction per source.",
      "testStrategy": "1. For each connector, ingest a representative sample of data and verify that the extracted metadata (author, timestamps, cross-references, etc.) is present and correctly populated in the output objects. 2. For JIRA, use the REST API to fetch issues and confirm that metadata such as reporter, assignee, timestamps, and linked issues are captured[1][5]. 3. For Confluence, verify that page hierarchy and cross-references are extracted. 4. For Git, check that commit metadata and file relationships are included. 5. Confirm that the metadata is accessible to the graph processing pipeline and that no changes to the public connector interfaces have occurred. 6. Validate that metadata extraction can be toggled via configuration. 7. Review and test documentation updates for accuracy.",
      "status": "pending",
      "dependencies": [
        4
      ],
      "priority": "medium",
